pportunity to chart the nature of social change in a particular locality over the last 50 years; includes discussions of social and cultural variations in family life, focusing on younger as well as older generations; explores not only what happens within family-households but also what happens within networks of kin across different households and shows the way changing patterns of employment affect kinship networks and how geographical mobility co-exists with the maintenance of strong kinship ties. The findings will be of interest to students of sociology, social anthropology, social policy, women's studies, gender studies and human geography at undergraduate and postgraduate level.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFamilieszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aFamilieszWaleszSwansea. 0aSocial changezGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Marriage & Family.2bisacsh1 aDavies, Charlotte, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 awithHarris, Chris, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995z97831111962130 cprintz978186134788640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847423603423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847423603/original  a978-3-11-119621-3  Bristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995c1995d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles